==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Plight
<hw>Plight</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>pliten</ets>; probably
through Old French, fr. LL. <ets>plectare</ets>, L. <ets>plectere</ets>.
See <er>Plait</er>, <er>Ply</er>.]</ety> <def>To weave; to braid; to
fold; to plait.</def><mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧To sew and
<xex>plight</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧<-- in the sense of fold, = pleat [plait 2 in
MW10]--> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>plighted</qex> garment of divers colors.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plight</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Plight
<hw>Plight</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A network; a plait; a
fold; rarely a garment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Many a folded
<xex>plight</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧<-- = pleat --> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plight</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Plight
<hw>Plight</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>pliht</ets> danger,
engagement, AS. <ets>pliht</ets> danger, fr. <ets>ple⟦oacute⟧n</ets> to
risk; akin to D. <ets>plicht</ets> duty, G. <ets>pflicht</ets>, Dan.
<ets>pligt</ets>. ⟦root⟧28. Cf. <er>Play</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>That which is exposed to risk; that which is plighted or pledged;
security; a gage; a pledge.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧That lord whose hand must take
my <xex>plight</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Perh. the same word as <ets>plight</ets> a pledge,
but at least influenced by OF. <ets>plite</ets>, <ets>pliste</ets>,
<ets>ploit</ets>, <ets>ploi</ets>, a condition, state; cf. E.
<ets>plight</ets> to fold, and F. <ets>pli</ets> a fold, habit,
<ets>plier</ets> to fold, E. <ets>ply</ets>.]</ety> <def>Condition;
state; -- risk, or exposure to danger, often being implied; <as>as, a
luckless <ex>plight</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Your <xex>plight</xex> is
pitied.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To bring our craft all in another <qex>plight</qex></q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plight</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Plight
<hw>Plight</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Plighted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Plighting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>plihtan</ets> to
expose to danger, <ets>pliht</ets> danger;cf. D. ver<ets>plichten</ets>
to oblige, engage, impose a duty, G. ver<ets>pflichten</ets>, Sw.
f⟦oum⟧r<ets>plikta</ets>, Dan. for<ets>pligte</ets>. See
<er>Plight</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pledge; to
give as a pledge for the performance of some act; as, to
<xex>plight</xex> faith, honor, word; -- never applied to property or
goods.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ To do them <xex>plighte</xex> their troth.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>plighted</qex> his right hand⟦br⟧
Unto another love, and to another land.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here my inviolable faith I <qex>plight</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To promise; to engage; to betroth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before its setting hour, divide⟦br⟧
The bridegroom from the <qex>plighted</qex> bride.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plighter</ent>⟦br⟧
